title: For Sale/Trade:  Want to Solve the Gun Dealer Listings Issue?
postcontent:
The fix is easy.  

1.  Go to armslist.com. 

2.  Click the "Nebraska" link. 

3.  Click on the "All Categories" link. 

4.  Under ""For Sale By," check the box next to "Private Party."

The resulting page will have all professional dealers filtered out.  BOOKMARK THIS PAGE AS YOUR ARMSLIST "HOMEPAGE" FOR NEBRASKA.  

Alternatively, use (and bookmark--PLEASE BOOKMARK) this address: http://www.armslist.com/classifieds/search?location=nebraska&category=all&sellertype=1. This is the address of the page you get by following the above steps.

I have been using this method for several months, and it has been great.  Haven't seen a listing by you-know-who since I started using this method.

title: For Sale:  SMITH AND WESSON 357 MAGNUM 6" MODEL 19-3
postcontent:
FOR SALE: SMITH AND WESSON 357 MAGNUM 6" MODEL 19-3

Smith & Wesson Model (S&W) 19-3 Combat Magnum Revolver in caliber .357 Magnum (also uses .38 special). Blue steel construction with walnut checkered combat wood grips featuring the Smith & Wesson medallion., 6 inch pinned barrel, recessed six shot cylinder. Adjustable rear sight, target hammer, smooth wide trigger, double or single action operation. Original box and paperwork not present. Serial # K91676. Includes a zipper gun bag.

Interesting information about the K-Frame models:
"Retired Assistant Chief Patrol Inspector of the U.S. Border Patrol, famous gunfighter, and noted firearms and shooting skills writer Bill Jordan consulted with Smith & Wesson on the design and characteristics of the Model 19. Jordan's idea for a "peace officer's dream" sidearm was a heavy-barreled four-inch K-Frame .357 Magnum with a shrouded barrel like the big N-frame .357 and adjustable sights. After a year of experimentation with improved-strength steels and special heat-treating processes, the result was the .357 Combat Magnum (later designated Model 19), with the first serial-number gun (K260,000) presented to Jordan on November 15, 1955. The Model 19 was produced in blued carbon steel or nickel-plated steel with wood or rubber combat grips, 
an adjustable rear sight, semi-target hammer, serrated combat-type trigger, and was available in 2.5" (3": Model 66—rare), 4", or 6-inch barrel lengths. The weights are 30.5 ounces, 36 ounces, and 39 ounces, respectively. The 2.5- and 3-inch barrel versions had a round butts, while the others had square butts. The Model 19 was produced from 1957 (first model number stampings) to November 1999."

Smith and Wesson 357 Model 19-3 - 4" barrel is $650. Sorry no trades at this time.

title: For Sale:  SOLD: Tula Armory TOZ 78-05 Rifle
location: South of Ft. Worth, Burleson, Dallas, Texas
postcontent:
Sold - OK, short history lesson: Back around 2005 or so, the Russian Tula Armory began importing the TOZ (also called TO3 in Cyrillic) 78 series of rimfire rifles. The rimfire shooters in America and elsewhere absolutely ate these things up! The basic ones came with a blond beechwood stock and only fair fit and finish. However, they had a very good hammer-forged barrel and a fully-adjustable trigger (something rarely seen on American rifles anymore due to liability scares). Before the Russian imports stopped, the top of the line in the TOZ 78’s was the 78-05, which arrived during the late spring/early summer of 2007. This rifle had a much nicer beechwood stock, with a little figure in the wood, cut in a Bavarian Stalker style with cut checkering and a nice dark stain and oil finish. The 78-05 also had a medium-heavy hammer-forged target barrel, no factory sights, and dovetails cut to European specs (just under 11mm). This rifle was only available from the importers for a limited time, as Winchester licensed the TOZ 78 as the Winchester Wildcat, and the 78-05 as the Wildcat II Varmint, all announced in American Rifleman in September 2008. This original TOZ 78-05 stock has the “drooping” style buttstock typical of European stalking and hunting rifles, a slim contrasting wood buttplate, a small pancake cheeckpiece, a slim tapered forend with a Schnable tip (small and bulb shaped). This is one pretty rimfire rifle!

OK, enough history! I bought a couple of these rifles back in June of 2007, right after this variation was imported. I used one for a magazine review and shot the heck out of it before I sold it. The other was for a family member who decided they didn’t want it, so I stuck it in my “project” safe and there it has remained. A recent cleanout turned her up and now I am offering her to you.

Brand new, unfired except for factory testing (probably?), packed in a hard case with 4 magazines (2 – 5rd, 2 – 10rd) and a set of correct Euro-spec 1” rings to mount your favorite scope, its ready to go. This will make a fine squirrel or target rifle for NRA Sporter class. Nice enough to make a great Christmas present too! It’s been very hard to establish a value for this thing because there are exactly zero out there that I can find available, except for one in Australia for silly money. You can get pretty close using the Blue Book and adding features because they don’t have this specific rifle listed, although they do have the heavy barrel and the fancy stock as separate options. Based on their value, and one in a European price guide, the value should be around $420-450.

I am asking $400 for this one. If you have better documentation for a lower price, please contact me and I’ll consider what you have. Can do FTF in the Ft. Worth area of Tejas, or can have my FFL ship to yours for a flat $70 insured in CONUS. Funds need to be cash if FTF or USPS money order if we’re shipping. No trade offers please! It’s not that I’m not interested in other guns, I need the cash.

Contact me through this site or e-mail me directly at wpmchenry AT gmail DOT com (take that email spambots!). All e-mails will be answered promptly.

postcontent:
Barrett MRAD chambered in .338 Lapua and is Brand new in box.   
Ready to follow your every move, the MRAD adapts to a variety of user needs without sacrificing performance. With unfailing accuracy, this bolt-action system continues to define a whole new class of long-range precision rifles.
The MRAD rifle's user-changeable barrel system is just one example of this hardworking gun's modularity. The precision grade barrel can be removed by simply loosening two bolts using a standard Torx wrench. Besides reducing maintenance and logistical burdens, this unique design allows for user level caliber interchangeability and serviceability with the MRAD rifle's barrel kits.
The MRAD also boasts Barrett's fully adjustable match-grade trigger module, which is user accessible. The thumb-operated safety can be configured for left or right hand operation. The ambidextrous magazine release can be used intuitively while retaining a firing grip and cheek weld.
Integrated into the MRAD rifle's 7000 series aluminum upper receiver is a 21.75 inch M1913 rail with 30 MOA taper. The forward receiver is drilled and tapped for accessory rails to be mounted at the 3, 6 and 9 o'clock positions.
The MRAD stock is foldable for enhanced portability yet locks in as solid as a fixed-stock rifle, creating a rigid platform for consistent firing. During transport the stock folds and locks onto the bolt handle maintaining the same rifle width whether folded or extended.
Made of a temperature-resistant polymer, the adjustable cheek piece also offers a consistent rifle-to-user contact point. The rifle's length of pull can be set to five different positions with the push of a single button.
From its quick-detach sling mounts to the Barrett Multi-Role Brown color that blends into any environment - every detail of the MRAD has been carefully designed to create one thing: a high-performance rifle you can truly make your own.
